Upon me anyway.

00:12:30.830 --> 00:12:32.130
&gt;&gt; Patrick Rosal: Yep.

00:12:32.130 --> 00:12:33.430
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: And
I guess when that's true,

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:34.730
as well when it's a matter

00:12:34.730 --> 00:12:36.030
of marketing it's also
a matter of money.

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:38.480
A lot of people who would
consider themselves poets first

00:12:38.480 --> 00:12:40.250
and foremost that's like the
phrase I always have it's

00:12:40.250 --> 00:12:42.840
like etched on my mind; I
don't know where it came from.

00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:45.110
You're not going to
make money that way.

00:12:45.110 --> 00:12:48.710
So, yeah you're going to
branch into other fields

00:12:48.710 --> 00:12:50.230
and I think it's true.

00:12:50.230 --> 00:12:53.720
I think like a genre
is something that flows

00:12:53.720 --> 00:12:55.020
out of you as you're writing.

00:12:55.020 --> 00:12:56.630
It's like the form
comes out of you.

00:12:56.630 --> 00:12:59.970
It's I don't think about whether
I'm writing poetry or prose

00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:01.800
when I'm doing the
actual writing,

00:13:01.800 --> 00:13:05.320
and since as you mentioned
Twitter and things like that,

00:13:05.320 --> 00:13:07.170
on Twitter I'm known as a poet.

00:13:07.170 --> 00:13:08.520
So, when people come
to my readings

00:13:08.520 --> 00:13:11.650
and they hear me read
anything they call it a poem,

00:13:11.650 --> 00:13:13.470
because like they
think that's what I am.

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:15.210
I think that's as
good as anything.

00:13:15.210 --> 00:13:17.120
I mean, that makes as
much sense, but yeah,

00:13:17.120 --> 00:13:19.330
a huge part of it is that,
you know, like we're not going

00:13:19.330 --> 00:13:21.100
to make a ton of
money doing this.

00:13:21.100 --> 00:13:25.790
So, we're going to have to
branch out a little bit.

00:13:25.790 --> 00:13:27.090
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: So, wait.

00:13:27.090 --> 00:13:32.420
When you set out to
write, you're not thinking

00:13:32.420 --> 00:13:36.520
on what I'm writing,
you're not category; really?

00:13:36.520 --> 00:13:37.820
Like you.

00:13:37.820 --> 00:13:39.120
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: You
know what book you're in.

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:40.420
That's what's true of me.

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:41.880
I know what book I'm in, but
even in the midst of something

00:13:41.880 --> 00:13:43.740
like [inaudible] I'm writing
something that's essentially

00:13:43.740 --> 00:13:45.580
along the poem, so not really.

00:13:45.580 --> 00:13:47.620
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: It's kind of
fascinating, because you,

00:13:47.620 --> 00:13:52.430
you know, there are; I mean we
all know there are differences

00:13:52.430 --> 00:13:53.730
for example right?

00:13:53.730 --> 00:13:56.520
I mean, like for, you know,
you have we're mostly talking

00:13:56.520 --> 00:13:58.200
about creative nonfiction,

00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:01.860
prose almost demands you
declaring it true or not

00:14:01.860 --> 00:14:05.030
because there are these
categorizations that we've grown

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:07.230
up with, they're fiction,
they're nonfiction, you know,

00:14:07.230 --> 00:14:11.830
poetry you have a voice and
there's a little bit more leeway

00:14:11.830 --> 00:14:14.920
in there, and of course,
there's; you know,

00:14:14.920 --> 00:14:16.220
one of the different things.

00:14:16.220 --> 00:14:17.520
&gt;&gt; Camille T. Dungy: Right,

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:22.690
but I think that in poetry
also I have a responsibility

00:14:22.690 --> 00:14:26.170
to capital T truth, not facts.

00:14:26.170 --> 00:14:28.930
That's not what I'm
talking about.

00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:32.910
I'm talking about real
truth; is this believable

00:14:32.910 --> 00:14:35.280
to another human heart, right?

00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:40.630
And so, how is that different
than truth in nonfiction, right?

00:14:40.630 --> 00:14:41.930
So, I think there's
different things

00:14:41.930 --> 00:14:43.290
that you're doing with the line.

00:14:43.290 --> 00:14:45.000
That often when I start

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:49.700
into writing nonfiction I've
released myself from one

00:14:49.700 --> 00:14:53.460
of poetry's great super powers
which is that the line break

00:14:53.460 --> 00:14:57.100
at the end you have all these
opportunities for variation,

00:14:57.100 --> 00:14:58.910
but there's really
beautiful poetry

00:14:58.910 --> 00:15:02.360
that doesn't depend
upon the line either,

00:15:02.360 --> 00:15:07.360
so I think sometimes I
know there's an essay

00:15:07.360 --> 00:15:09.670
at the very beginning
of "Guidebook

00:15:09.670 --> 00:15:12.060
to Relative Strangers" where
I'm at an artist colony

00:15:12.060 --> 00:15:15.590
and somebody said like
a ridiculous thing,

00:15:15.590 --> 00:15:19.040
and I it was maddening
and rather

00:15:19.040 --> 00:15:23.800
than go drink I went
and wrote about it.

00:15:23.800 --> 00:15:28.060
And so, that I knew like
I'm angry about this thing

00:15:28.060 --> 00:15:31.380
and I'm going to write into
that anger and that writing

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:35.230
into that anger requires
some sort of [inaudible]

00:15:35.230 --> 00:15:39.550
of information and history and
context that it's probably going

00:15:39.550 --> 00:15:43.620
to be too bulky, right, and so
as I start writing it becomes

00:15:43.620 --> 00:15:47.690
and essay and that becomes clear
as I'm writing, but mostly I was

00:15:47.690 --> 00:15:53.110
like I am filled with rage
and really practical way

00:15:53.110 --> 00:15:55.610
of dissipating that rage
is to get to the page.

00:15:55.610 --> 00:15:58.530
And so, I might have written
a poem, right with that.

00:15:58.530 --> 00:16:02.260
It's just in this case I
was driving towards a point

00:16:02.260 --> 00:16:06.460
at length and that ended up
becoming an essay for me.

00:16:06.460 --> 00:16:07.860
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: There was
that funny [inaudible] a couple

00:16:07.860 --> 00:16:09.740
of years ago, where
like the it turned

00:16:09.740 --> 00:16:11.990
out The New Yorker was
still fact-checking poems

00:16:11.990 --> 00:16:13.390
and there was like a line

00:16:13.390 --> 00:16:14.940
in a Michael Robbins'
poem I think it was.

00:16:14.940 --> 00:16:17.880
It was like the Swedes invented
refrigeration and they wrote

00:16:17.880 --> 00:16:21.090
and they were like "No,
they actually didn't."

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:24.710
And I think that they stopped
after that point, because I know

00:16:24.710 --> 00:16:26.700
that I had like some poems
and then after that I'm like,

00:16:26.700 --> 00:16:28.010
"Oh those are full of lies."

00:16:28.010 --> 00:16:32.720
So, it's good that they're
not doing that anymore.

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:34.520
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: So, go with
me here and imagine a world

00:16:34.520 --> 00:16:38.810
where we don't have these
categorizations than and how,

00:16:38.810 --> 00:16:43.000
so here, you know, did
you; when you came to write

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:46.880
and you know writing and reading
when you were a kid let's say,

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:50.520
did you come through poems
and then come through?

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:53.540
No, so it really is,
you're shaking your head.

00:16:53.540 --> 00:16:54.840
&gt;&gt; Patrick Rosal: I didn't.

00:16:54.840 --> 00:16:56.140
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: Yeah, yeah.

00:16:56.140 --> 00:16:58.320
&gt;&gt; Patrick Rosal: I was
kind of a typical product

00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:01.750
of American education which is
to say that I was intimidated

00:17:01.750 --> 00:17:05.010
by poetry and I thought that it
was completely apart from me.

00:17:05.010 --> 00:17:07.040
It was apart from my
family as traditions.

00:17:07.040 --> 00:17:13.930
It was literary with a capital
L. It was up there and so, yeah,

00:17:13.930 --> 00:17:18.420
poems were not part
of me growing up.

00:17:18.420 --> 00:17:23.500
They were part of my entrance
as an adult into loving books,

00:17:23.500 --> 00:17:26.360
into you know, really
dedicating my life in terms

00:17:26.360 --> 00:17:31.150
of having a formal
relationship with language,

00:17:31.150 --> 00:17:36.150
but yeah poetry was not, it
wasn't something that was sort

00:17:36.150 --> 00:17:39.470
of engrained in me
very early on.

00:17:39.470 --> 00:17:40.900
&gt;&gt; Camille T. Dungy: And I'm
going to say the opposite.

00:17:40.900 --> 00:17:43.680
My grandmother was
a school librarian,

00:17:43.680 --> 00:17:45.320
an elementary school librarian.

00:17:45.320 --> 00:17:50.190
Books were all around and I was
like ecumenical in my reading.

00:17:50.190 --> 00:17:51.710
I was just like there
was a book.

00:17:51.710 --> 00:17:54.370
It's almost like
Patricia's audiences.

00:17:54.370 --> 00:17:55.670
Like it was a book.

00:17:55.670 --> 00:17:56.970
I was just reading a book.

00:17:56.970 --> 00:18:03.850
It just could be anything
and I trapped through poetry

00:18:03.850 --> 00:18:07.570
when I started going in college
and graduate school in poetry,

00:18:07.570 --> 00:18:10.940
but even in graduate school
I remember what I was in one

00:18:10.940 --> 00:18:14.160
of those programs that
was very, very isolated.

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:16.710
Like you were in the poetry
trap and you weren't allowed

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:18.090
to take any of the fiction traps

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:19.490
and nonfiction wasn't
even a thing

00:18:19.490 --> 00:18:22.060
that they were talking
about at that time.

00:18:22.060 --> 00:18:27.830
So, the explosion of nonfiction
is a fascinating space for a lot

00:18:27.830 --> 00:18:30.550
of us to be writing is,
but that was a trap.

00:18:30.550 --> 00:18:33.450
But I was sneaking away
writing stories and working

00:18:33.450 --> 00:18:35.970
with the fiction people and
trying to figure out how to,

00:18:35.970 --> 00:18:40.780
how to get a kind of
training in prose even

00:18:40.780 --> 00:18:43.690
when I was being disallowed
from it because I was a poet

00:18:43.690 --> 00:18:47.180
and that was what my
job was supposed to be.

00:18:47.180 --> 00:18:50.640
I think when, when my
daughter was born I found

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:56.240
that prose was a way that I can
write because of that training.

00:18:56.240 --> 00:18:58.340
That training in poetry
I have been trained

00:18:58.340 --> 00:19:00.930
in now what I've come to call
the person from poor lot school

00:19:00.930 --> 00:19:04.560
of poetry where like when you
write a poem if anybody knocks

00:19:04.560 --> 00:19:07.220
on the door or interrupts
it all the poem is destroyed

00:19:07.220 --> 00:19:08.520
and you can't, you know,

00:19:08.520 --> 00:19:11.790
then that's why we didn't get
the rest of Kubla Khan, right?

00:19:11.790 --> 00:19:15.400
Like, but when you have a
kid like you have the person

00:19:15.400 --> 00:19:18.470
from poor lot knocking on
your door every five minutes

00:19:18.470 --> 00:19:22.080
and because I think I
was untrained in prose,

00:19:22.080 --> 00:19:24.550
I can just keep writing
through it and around it,

00:19:24.550 --> 00:19:27.480
because I had already
fiercely figured out how to do

00:19:27.480 --> 00:19:30.840
that against all odds
and so it was a wild,

00:19:30.840 --> 00:19:35.680
but before my training in my
training in poetry was able

00:19:35.680 --> 00:19:40.020
to be overtaken again by
that freedom that I had found

00:19:40.020 --> 00:19:41.890
in prose which was
from the leftover

00:19:41.890 --> 00:19:45.460
of just you reading something
and you writing it in response.

00:19:45.460 --> 00:19:46.840
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood:
Maybe that's why nonfiction

00:19:46.840 --> 00:19:49.520
at the moment feels so
elastic too, if it's true

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:51.450
that because I don't have
higher education, I don't know,

00:19:51.450 --> 00:19:53.510
but what you're saying
resonates with things I've heard

00:19:53.510 --> 00:19:57.010
from other people, if those
traps are so strongly defined

00:19:57.010 --> 00:19:58.910
and people want to flee
those a little bit,

00:19:58.910 --> 00:20:03.150
maybe they've found this other
ground or this other capacity.

00:20:03.150 --> 00:20:04.930
Maybe that is the place

00:20:04.930 --> 00:20:07.420
that we've taken those
things, I don't know.

00:20:07.420 --> 00:20:09.270
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: Patricia
you had said,

00:20:09.270 --> 00:20:13.110
wrote I had asked a
question about whether poetry

00:20:13.110 --> 00:20:15.070
and prose reaches
different audiences

00:20:15.070 --> 00:20:18.290
and you said there's a certain
percentage in my audience

00:20:18.290 --> 00:20:21.330
that considers anything I write
in poetry, because I am a poet.

00:20:21.330 --> 00:20:23.680
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: Yeah,
but I think that's why, I mean,

00:20:23.680 --> 00:20:25.200
that's okay yeah, right.

00:20:25.200 --> 00:20:27.400
It's like it's a matter of
how you get them in the door

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:29.530
and then you can read
whatever you want to them

00:20:29.530 --> 00:20:32.610
and they have no control over
it, so again, it's a book.

00:20:32.610 --> 00:20:33.910
It's a reading.

00:20:33.910 --> 00:20:37.810
You know, what happens in it
is sort of amorphous material

00:20:37.810 --> 00:20:40.540
that the form is imposed
upon from without.

00:20:40.540 --> 00:20:43.590
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: I it's, you're
wrapping my world a little bit

00:20:43.590 --> 00:20:44.890
because I have a
lot of questions.

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:48.730
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood:
You ask the questions.

00:20:48.730 --> 00:20:50.950
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: I know,
because I have questions.

00:20:50.950 --> 00:20:53.110
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: You ask
the questions that interest you.

00:20:53.110 --> 00:20:54.710
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: Well,
my question is

00:20:54.710 --> 00:20:57.210
about how one informs the
other and they'll run,

00:20:57.210 --> 00:21:04.440
and where you know, like you
know Camille had said let's

00:21:04.440 --> 00:21:06.980
breakdown the walls and that.

00:21:06.980 --> 00:21:10.600
You know, we have prose
writers who say don't put me

00:21:10.600 --> 00:21:14.340
on a poetry panel
because I can't.

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:15.640
&gt;&gt; Patrick Rosal: Yeah.

00:21:15.640 --> 00:21:16.940
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: Judge poetry.

00:21:16.940 --> 00:21:19.700
&gt;&gt; Camille T. Dungy: Well, I
mean I will say that I think

00:21:19.700 --> 00:21:25.900
that as how to train as a poet,
I have an attention to word

00:21:25.900 --> 00:21:28.880
like at the word
level and phrase level

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:36.360
and the music level the prose
writers are not necessarily

00:21:36.360 --> 00:21:37.660
trained in.

00:21:37.660 --> 00:21:39.860
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood:
They're jealous about it too.

00:21:39.860 --> 00:21:41.160
&gt;&gt; Camille T. Dungy:
As poets, right?

00:21:41.160 --> 00:21:45.070
And so that may be what
one of the differences

00:21:45.070 --> 00:21:51.790
between poets writing
prose is that like I found

00:21:51.790 --> 00:21:55.520
when I remember like right
after graduate school I tried

00:21:55.520 --> 00:22:01.120
to write a novel and
that just didn't work,

00:22:01.120 --> 00:22:05.030
because I was writing the novel
and then I would have to break

00:22:05.030 --> 00:22:10.600
for the day and I would go
back as I would with a poem

00:22:10.600 --> 00:22:15.910
and I would read everything
I've written before

00:22:15.910 --> 00:22:18.880
to get the sonic quality.

00:22:18.880 --> 00:22:20.420
Well once you hit page 10,

00:22:20.420 --> 00:22:24.020
like my whole writing session
was rereading what I had written

00:22:24.020 --> 00:22:29.340
the day before and I would
tell that to prose writers

00:22:29.340 --> 00:22:34.840
that would be like, it's
not going to work for you.

00:22:34.840 --> 00:22:36.220
Like that's crazy.

00:22:36.220 --> 00:22:40.030
So, and I didn't do it with the
book of essays all the time,

00:22:40.030 --> 00:22:43.210
but there would be
some days and I know

00:22:43.210 --> 00:22:51.030
that prose writers do this, so
don't come at me prose writers,

00:22:51.030 --> 00:22:55.990
but you don't pay attention
to the words, but I do think

00:22:55.990 --> 00:23:01.630
that poets have been trained
usually to pay attention

00:23:01.630 --> 00:23:06.800
at the word level, the phoning
level a little bit differently

00:23:06.800 --> 00:23:13.340
than how prose writers do
and that, that may be one

00:23:13.340 --> 00:23:18.160
of the uniquenesses between
the two of us, right.

00:23:18.160 --> 00:23:21.500
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: I think
it may be even be inherent.

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:24.570
I don't know if it training.

00:23:24.570 --> 00:23:28.920
I notice that I get stuck
on words a lot more easily.

00:23:28.920 --> 00:23:32.670
I notice that there were
things when I was a kid

00:23:32.670 --> 00:23:37.410
that I did not understand
certain idioms that I would pour

00:23:37.410 --> 00:23:42.130
over and pour over
because I didn't get them;

00:23:42.130 --> 00:23:43.530
jokes I didn't understand.

00:23:43.530 --> 00:23:46.090
I still don't get the chicken
butt thing and I never will.

00:23:46.090 --> 00:23:48.810
No one can explain it to me.

00:23:48.810 --> 00:23:51.730
I had a student who asked me,

00:23:51.730 --> 00:23:57.490
she was like sometimes
I read poetry

00:23:57.490 --> 00:24:06.730
and I just don't understand
it on a basic sense level.

00:24:06.730 --> 00:24:11.730
I was like, if your
body understands it,

00:24:11.730 --> 00:24:13.580
you understand it enough.

00:24:13.580 --> 00:24:14.880
You have enough of it.

00:24:14.880 --> 00:24:20.130
You know what you need to
know and I think to be honest.

00:24:20.130 --> 00:24:24.380
&gt;&gt; Camille T. Dungy: For
her that's not enough.

00:24:24.380 --> 00:24:27.020
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: Well, but
I think it was anxiety, yeah,

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:31.440
so what I told her
was that it is enough.

00:24:31.440 --> 00:24:35.130
Like if your body is
responding you know something

00:24:35.130 --> 00:24:41.210
about this poem that maybe
your head doesn't know yet.

00:24:41.210 --> 00:24:44.100
But I think it's true maybe
that we are the people

00:24:44.100 --> 00:24:48.130
who misunderstand things,
that we misread things,

00:24:48.130 --> 00:24:51.190
that we transpose
words and a lot

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:56.250
of times I'll misread something
and it sounds better to me.

00:24:56.250 --> 00:24:59.960
So, I don't know if it's
a thing where, you know,

00:24:59.960 --> 00:25:04.180
we're drawn to that training
because it's something

00:25:04.180 --> 00:25:08.750
that we already kind of do,
like that might just be me,

00:25:08.750 --> 00:25:12.110
but I get stuck on stuff
in a way that is almost

00:25:12.110 --> 00:25:17.000
like a childish way and that's
why I pay so much attention

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:19.110
to it, because I have to.

00:25:19.110 --> 00:25:20.970
It's just like how I'm wired.

00:25:20.970 --> 00:25:25.200
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: Why don't
we take, I want to get

00:25:25.200 --> 00:25:31.100
into a little bit of the
subject matter that you.

00:25:31.100 --> 00:25:32.400
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: Sure.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:33.700
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: All write about,

00:25:33.700 --> 00:25:39.890
but why don't we take a
break and do some reading.

00:25:39.890 --> 00:25:41.190
&gt;&gt; Patricia Lockwood: Sure.

00:25:41.190 --> 00:25:42.970
&gt;&gt; Amy Stolls: Can you
do; who would like to?

00:25:42.970 --> 00:25:44.640
Should we go?

00:25:44.640 --> 00:25:46.450
Patrick would you like to read?

00:25:46.450 --> 00:25:48.610
&gt;&gt; Patrick Rosal: I don't
know what this is [laughter].

00:25:48.610 --> 00:25:56.250
I'm doing work around the race
riots in Watsonville in 1930,

00:25:56.250 --> 00:25:57.640
Watsonville, California.

00:25:57.640 --> 00:26:00.520
There were Filipino
farmworkers who were dancing

00:26:00.520 --> 00:26:02.520
with White women in taxi
dance halls and they,

00:26:02.520 --> 00:26:06.600
the White community formed
posses to hunt Filipino's down,

00:26:06.600 --> 00:26:08.640
threw them over the
Pajaro River Bridge,

00:26:08.640 --> 00:26:12.190
went out to the bunkhouse which
was four miles from downtown

00:26:12.190 --> 00:26:18.980
and one of the people from the
posses shot through the wall

00:26:18.980 --> 00:26:27.220
into the bunkhouse and killed a
young man named Fermin Tobera.

00:26:27.220 --> 00:26:29.110
So, I'm doing a cite, I
didn't even curse yet.

00:26:29.110 --> 00:26:32.420
I'm doing a cite-specific
performance.

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:39.340
I hope to do a cite-specific
performance out there

00:26:39.340 --> 00:26:41.790
in Watsonville, California.

00:26:41.790 --> 00:26:43.240
I'm writing around it.

00:26:43.240 --> 00:26:47.670
I'm doing drawings and all
kinds of things The only thing

00:26:47.670 --> 00:26:52.830
that you need to know about
this is that I'm an intralocular

00:26:52.830 --> 00:26:57.260
with these monomes the
Filipino farmworkers from 1930

00:26:57.260 --> 00:26:58.660
and I don't know who's dead.

00:26:58.660 --> 00:27:00.510
It's either them or me.

00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:03.840
I maybe a ghost visiting
them and one of the things

00:27:03.840 --> 00:27:05.770
that they've come
to do over time is

00:27:05.770 --> 00:27:08.770
to make kites inside
of this bunkhouse.

00:27:08.770 --> 00:27:10.070
"Here is a lie.

00:27:10.070 --> 00:27:12.990
The kite maker and his
companions work hard.

00:27:12.990 --> 00:27:14.790
They get up under
an orange-blue dawn.

00:27:14.790 --> 00:27:17.430
If they dream there's no time
to think about the dreams

00:27:17.430 --> 00:27:19.200
of visions of roosters
thrashing deep in the water.

00:27:19.200 --> 00:27:20.680
The blade still tied
to their ankles.

00:27:20.680 --> 00:27:22.060
The birds aren't drowning,
but they clearly don't belong.

00:27:22.060 --> 00:27:23.360
They're kicking their
feet, scratching,

00:27:23.360 --> 00:27:24.660
turning in the swirls
of undercurrent.

00:27:24.660 --> 00:27:25.960
The men always wake up before
they know if the cocks drown

00:27:25.960 --> 00:27:27.260
or grow fins or gills or
get swooped up by nets

00:27:27.260 --> 00:27:28.560
and dropped back into a yard

00:27:28.560 --> 00:27:29.860
where the animals
make more sense,

00:27:29.860 --> 00:27:31.160
into the fields,
hotter and hotter.

00:27:31.160 --> 00:27:32.460
Every day, I try to look more
carefully, see more deeply

00:27:32.460 --> 00:27:33.760
from all the way out here
this incredible distance.

00:27:33.760 --> 00:27:35.060
I'm younger than these
men after all, and yet,

00:27:35.060 --> 00:27:36.360
I'm older than them too.

00:27:36.360 --> 00:27:37.660
They are as young as
17 and one who looks

00:27:37.660 --> 00:27:38.960
like my grandfather barely 23.

00:27:38.960 --> 00:27:40.260
Sometimes I get close enough
to them I can ask questions.

00:27:40.260 --> 00:27:41.560
When they speak, it's as if
they aren't speaking to me,

00:27:41.560 --> 00:27:42.860
but to one another or
a lover left behind.

00:27:42.860 --> 00:27:44.160
I can't tell if it's because
they are too far away in time

00:27:44.160 --> 00:27:45.460
and miles or if they
just refuse to tell me

00:27:45.460 --> 00:27:46.760
about the knife they're holding,
the sound of the blade pulling

00:27:46.760 --> 00:27:48.060
through the stalks,
what the ground tastes

00:27:48.060 --> 00:27:49.360
like when they have to
suck the blood from the cut

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:50.660
in the thumb they
made themselves

00:27:50.660 --> 00:27:51.960
and not lose the
rhythm of reaping.

00:27:51.960 --> 00:27:53.260
I don't blame them.

00:27:53.260 --> 00:27:54.560
There's nothing to the
work after a while.

00:27:54.560 --> 00:27:55.860
There is no thinking.

00:27:55.860 --> 00:27:57.160
There was a time when the
men had a deliberateness

00:27:57.160 --> 00:27:58.460
and a strangeness to the
bending and cutting and pulling

00:27:58.460 --> 00:27:59.760
when they first arrived just
after White men took their names

00:27:59.760 --> 00:28:01.060
and asked them if
they could read,

00:28:01.060 --> 00:28:02.360
asked if they had
wives back home.

00:28:02.360 --> 00:28:03.660
There was a time the men,
these monomes thought

00:28:03.660 --> 00:28:04.960
about this comparing
the first lettuce

00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:06.260
to the next making sure
they got the whole head.

00:28:06.260 --> 00:28:07.560
It doesn't take a
week to stop thinking.

00:28:07.560 --> 00:28:08.860
You're body just goes and
your mind does other things.

00:28:08.860 --> 00:28:10.160
First it dreams of the
faces it left behind.

00:28:10.160 --> 00:28:11.460
How happy they'll be to see you
again to build a house and buy

00:28:11.460 --> 00:28:13.010
so many fat pigs
and goats and cows.

00:28:13.010 --> 00:28:15.370
You caught me lying again.

00:28:15.370 --> 00:28:21.280
They are thinking of sleep or
they are thinking of the uncle

00:28:21.280 --> 00:28:23.110
who slapped them on the back

00:28:23.110 --> 00:28:27.860
or across their teeth the day
before they left their village,

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:31.760
or they are thinking of
slitting the foreman's neck.

00:28:31.760 --> 00:28:35.770
They are thinking of hanging
themselves from a tree.

00:28:35.770 --> 00:28:40.480
They are thinking of swimming
in the ocean, the water salt

00:28:40.480 --> 00:28:42.630
which is different
from the spicy,

00:28:42.630 --> 00:28:46.310
muddy salt of their
own heads and armpits.

00:28:46.310 --> 00:28:50.210
They are thinking of swimming
all the way back home.

00:28:50.210 --> 00:28:53.300
They are thinking no
will remember their names

00:28:53.300 --> 00:28:54.880
when they get back.

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:59.150
They are thinking of
changing their names anyway.

00:28:59.150 --> 00:29:01.420
Edison is a good name.

00:29:01.420 --> 00:29:04.460
They are thinking of going
back to another province

00:29:04.460 --> 00:29:09.100
and finding a wife who will
call them Edison, a famous name

00:29:09.100 --> 00:29:13.570
as if a name could
change a face sun bait.

00:29:13.570 --> 00:29:16.520
No one weeps anymore.

00:29:16.520 --> 00:29:18.400
That's my last lie.

00:29:18.400 --> 00:29:25.010
But this man here because he no
longer has to think about how

00:29:25.010 --> 00:29:29.410
to grip the handle or the
angle of the knife's edge,

00:29:29.410 --> 00:29:31.540
because he is quick with
his work but not too quick.

00:29:31.540 --> 00:29:32.840
He can think of something else.

00:29:32.840 --> 00:29:34.640
He can think of making kites."

