00:35:00.690 --> 00:35:02.630
and then this is a poem called

00:35:02.630 --> 00:35:06.450
"Frequently Asked
Questions, Number 7."

00:35:06.450 --> 00:35:13.490
Is it difficult to get away from
it all once you've had a child?

00:35:13.490 --> 00:35:18.020
I am swaying in the galley,
working to appease this infant

00:35:18.020 --> 00:35:24.260
who is not fussing, but will
be fussing if I don't move.

00:35:24.260 --> 00:35:27.660
When a black steward
enters the cramped space

00:35:27.660 --> 00:35:30.010
at the back of the plane.

00:35:30.010 --> 00:35:32.430
He stands by the food
carts prepping his service.

00:35:32.430 --> 00:35:38.330
Then he is holding his throat
the way we hold our throats

00:35:38.330 --> 00:35:42.670
when we think we
are going to die.

00:35:42.670 --> 00:35:44.090
I'm sorry.

00:35:44.090 --> 00:35:46.400
I'm so sorry.

00:35:46.400 --> 00:35:47.990
He is crying.

00:35:47.990 --> 00:35:52.930
My God. What they did to us.

00:35:52.930 --> 00:35:57.650
I am swaying lest my brown baby
girl make a nuisance of herself,

00:35:57.650 --> 00:36:01.840
and the steward is
crying honest man tears.

00:36:01.840 --> 00:36:08.510
Seeing you holding your daughter
like that for the first time,

00:36:08.510 --> 00:36:12.620
I understand what
they did to us.

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:19.620
All those women sold away from
their babies, he whispers.

00:36:19.620 --> 00:36:21.940
I am at a loss now.

00:36:21.940 --> 00:36:27.920
Perhaps I could fabricate an
image to represent this agony,

00:36:27.920 --> 00:36:33.350
but the steward has walked
into the galley of history.

00:36:33.350 --> 00:36:38.510
There is nothing
figurative about us."

